Okay, so this commit fundamentally changes how we manage the `acomp_ctx` (compression context) for each CPU in zswap.  Previously, we allocated this context when a CPU came online and destroyed it when it went offline. Now, the context is allocated when the zswap pool is created or a CPU hotplugs in and *retained* until the pool is destroyed. The primary change is the removal of the `zswap_cpu_comp_dead` callback. I've been carefully walking through the changes to ensure there are no subtle race conditions or memory leaks introduced.

